notesStmt.note: Caption title (f. 1r): Leonardi Aretini in libros ethicorum proemium.
Incipit (f. 1r): Aristotelis ethicorum libros latinos facere nuper institui.
Incipit (f. 5r): Omnis ars omnisque doctrina similiter autem & actus & electio bonum quoddam appetere videtur.

msIdentifier.repository: Kislak Center for Special Collections, Rare Books and Manuscripts

msContents.summary: Aristotle's Nicomachean Ethics, translated from the Greek by Leonardo Bruni Aretino with the translator's introduction and dedication.

supportDesc.extent: 120 leaves : 262 x 190 (165 x 104) mm. bound to 273 x 197 mm
supportDesc.foliation: Parchment, 120; [1-2], 3-120; modern foliation in pencil, upper right recto; contemporary foliation in ink, in upper right recto.

layoutDesc.layout: Written in 27 long lines; ruled in drypoint; some prickings visible.

decoDesc.decoNote: 5-line ornamented initial in red and black ink (f. 1r); 4-line illuminated initials in gold, blue, pink, and green, with interlaced ornamentation (for example, f. 84v).

origin.p: Written in Italy in the 15th century (Zacour-Hirsch).

history.provenance: Formerly owned by Sir Thomas Phillipps, Ms. 16239 (note, inside upper cover); George Dunn (bookplate, inside upper cover); Laurence W. Hodson (bookplate, inside upper cover).
